      "role": "user",
      "content": "Right, so it's a race condition. But I'm trying to understand why it feels so chaotic. Even when we scale up the pods, the error pops up in different places, almost like it's lurking in the background until traffic hits a certain rhythm.\n\nDo you think there's any way we can prevent the state machine from getting into that \"unexpected\" phase, or is the whole architecture just inherently prone to these weird, sudden breakdowns?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The chaotic behavior you're describing is often referred to as a \"hidden failure\" or \"latent failure\". It's a classic problem in distributed systems, where a single bad actor or a subtle failure can cause the entire system to fail catastrophically. In this case, it's possible that the state machine's design and the concurrent inventory_update_service calls are creating a perfect storm for these hidden failures to occur.\n\nWhile it's difficult to completely eliminate the possibility of these failures, there are some strategies you can use to mitigate them. One approach would be to introduce additional logging and monitoring to help identify the source of the failures, so you can take targeted action to address them. Another approach would be to consider implementing a form of \"fault injection\" or \"stress testing\" to help identify and harden against these types of failures.",
      "source": "target",
